When you see a <sprite name="colorless" tint=1> Energy symbol, that means any Energy will work. The <sprite name="water" tint=1> Energy in your hand will do just fine!
In this match, I want to teach you about Special Conditions.
My Beedrill made your Inteleon Poisoned, which means your Inteleon will continue to take 10 damage during Pokmon Checkup. That's a special step that happens after each of our turns.
Poisoned is just one Special Condition. You'll discover others as you keep playing Pokmon Trading Card Game Live!
One way to remove Special Conditions from your Pokmon is to get them out of the Active Spot.
Use Switch to swap in a Pokmon from your Bench.
Let's take a closer look at my Beedrill. There's something I want to show you.
Since my Beedrill has Weakness to <sprite name="fire" tint=1>, it will take double damage if you attack it with any <sprite name="fire" tint=1> Pokmon.
Wow, what a powerful hit! Great Knock Out!
Even though you're only taking 1 Prize card here, I don't have any Pokmon on my Bench, so you win!
Not only can Pokmon attack, but they also have useful Abilities that can help your strategy.
Unlike attacking, using an Ability usually won't end your turn.
However, most Pokmon Abilities can only be used once per turn.
Boss's Orders lets you switch 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokmon into their Active Spot. You get to pick!
Remember what I taught you about Weakness earlier?
Seems like there might be something to take note of on each of our Benches
Since we know that the Cinderace on your Bench will be strong against my Rillaboom, let's get it into the Active Spot.
You can retreat your Pokmon as long as you meet the Energy requirements!
You already have a Pokmon ready in the Active Spot! Go ahead and swing for a big attack!
Stadium cards are a special type of Trainer card that can affect the entire match! My Training Court lets me get the Energy I need from the discard pile.
And, just to make sure you don't have enough Energy to attack, I'll play Crushing Hammer, which lets me discard an Energy from your Pokmon if I flip heads.
Thanks to my Crushing Hammer, you don't have enough Energy to attack. However even though I played Training Court, you can use it as well!
Hmmm...Maybe I shouldn't have done that...
Stadium cards have all sorts of useful effects. Use Training Court to recover the <sprite name="metal" tint=1> Energy card I discarded!
Brave Blade is a powerful attack, but it has a drawback: Zacian <sprite name="v"> can't attack during the next turn, even if you have enough Energy.

As as luck would have it, you drew exactly what you needed to get out of this situation!
Air Balloon is a Pokmon Tool card, which means it can be attached to a Pokmon. And its effect will remain on the Pokmon as long as it's attached.
A green arrow appeared on Zacian <sprite name="v"> because Air Balloon reduced its Retreat Cost to 0. This lets you switch it out without a penalty. I'd say that's a positive effect!

Do you see how the red arrow went away once Zacian <sprite name="v"> moved to the Bench? If you can get it back to the Active Spot, you can attack again this turn! The Switch card in your hand will do just that.
Pokmon <sprite name="vMax"> are worth 3 Prize cards, so you win!

I'll help you through the first few parts of the match, and then we can have a real battle!

I have something I'd like to show you. Use that Quick Ball in your hand!
A couple things. First, you can always use this opportunity to look through the rest of your deck by selecting the All tab.
Advanced players use this as a tactic to figure out what's in their Prize cards, and they can strategize around that.
Feel free to browse here until you're ready. Then select Crobat <sprite name="v">.

I suggest playing as many cards as you can before you drag Crobat <sprite name="v"> to your Bench.
That is all I have left to teach. The rest of the battle is up to you.

Pokmon V and Pokmon VMAX are powerful, but if they get Knocked Out, your opponent gets to take extra Prize cards.
Eternatus VMAX's Eternal Zone Ability allows you to put up to 8 Pokmon on your Bench!
You can only evolve a Pokmon once per turn, and you cant evolve a Basic Pokmon on the turn you played it to the Bench.
Basic Pokmon can be put directly on your Bench, but Evolution Pokmon must be evolved from a lower-stage Pokmon that is already in play.
Quick Ball is a great card for finding any Basic Pokmon in your deck. You have to discard another card from your hand, though, so choose wisely!
Rare Candy lets you evolve a Basic Pokmon directly into a Stage 2skipping the Stage 1 entirely!
Make sure you have plenty of useful Trainer cards. Switch, Professors Research, and Bosss Orders are invaluable in almost every deck.
You can only play 1 Supporter card each turn, but you can play as many Item cards as youd like.
Air Balloon is a Tool card that reduces a Pokmons Retreat Cost by 2. Use it on a bulky Pokmon you need to get out of the Active Spot.
If you choose to go first, you can't attack until your second turn. However, Talonflame Vs Fast Flight is a special attack that you can use on your first turn!
Piers allows you to search your deck for any Energy card, even Special Energy!
Pay close attention to the Weakness and Resistance of your Pokmon and your opponent's Pokmon.
If you play a card like Level Ball that lets you search for a card, take the time to look at what else is in your deck. That way you can figure out what your Prize cards are.
Don't forget to attach an Energy card to 1 of your Pokmon each turn.
Are all of your important Pokmon in the discard pile? Use an Ordinary Rod to shuffle them back into your deck!
You win the match if your opponent has no more Pokmon in play, even if you haven't taken all of your Prize cards. If your opponent only has 1 Pokmon left, try to get an early win!
If you rely on using a lot of Abilities, be careful if your opponent plays Galarian Weezing. ItsNeutralizing Gas Ability will turn off all of your Abilities!
If you use Scoop Up Net to put a damaged Pokmon back into your hand, all the damage counters are removed!
Boss's Orders lets you switch a Pokmon from your opponent's Bench into battleand that can lead to an easy Knock Out!
Your Active Pokmon recovers from Special Conditions when you evolve it, move it to your Bench, or play a card like Full Heal.
If your Pokmon is Confused, you have to flip a coin before attacking. If tails, that Pokmon damages itself instead!
A Burned, Poisoned, or Confused Pokmon can still retreat, but a Pokmon that is Asleep or Paralyzed cannot.
Crobat V's Dark Asset is great when you need to draw more cards. Try to play other cards to reduce your hand size first so you can draw the most cards possible!
A Colorless symbol in an attack cost means you can use any type of Energy!
Having more cards in your hand means you have more options. Hop will help you draw even more cards.
Attacking always ends your turn. Make sure you've used all the Trainer cards and Abilities you need before attacking.
Galarian Zigzagoon's Headbutt Tantrum Ability lets you put 1 damage counter on any of your opponent's Pokmon when you play it onto your Bench. That may not seem like much, but it adds up!
The special text box on some Pokmon cards that says "rule" is called a Rule Box. Pokmon V, VMAX, V-UNION, VSTAR all have Rule Boxes.
Each Pokmon VSTAR has a special VSTAR Power. You can only use one VSTAR Power per game, so try to plan out the best time to use it!

You can win the game by taking all of your Prize cards, by Knocking Out your opponent's Active Pokmon when they have no Pokmon on the Bench, or if your opponent cannot draw a card at the beginning of their turn.
You can have only 4 of any card with the same name in a deck, other than basic Energy cards.
If your strategy relies on Abilities, watch out for cards like Path to the Peak that can turn those Abilities off!
Pokmon VSTAR have less HP than Pokmon VMAX, but they give up 2 Prize cards instead of 3 if they are Knocked Out!

Hello everyone. The Pokmon TCG Live game client has been updated today. Please see below for the list of changes:

Certain card attacks now correctly count amount of Energy provided, rather than number of Energy cards attached, when calculating damage.

Certain Abilities have been updated to no longer appear to the opponent that they are being activated if the player chose not to use the effect.

Shining Mew (SLG #40): The Legendary Guidance attack no longer causes a soft lock during Energy selection.

Shedinja (VIV #66): The Shell Survival Ability has been updated to prevent being put into play by effects other than Ninjask's Cast-Off Shell Ability.

Certain card effects that put a Pokmon from the discard pile onto the Bench can no longer fail to find if a valid target exists.

Damage Mover (SLG #58): Card has been updated to allow moving damage counters from a Pokmon that has only 1 or 2 damage counters on it.

HP and type overlay for Pokmon in play have been updated to be visible in all views throughout the match.

Elesa's Sparkle (FST #233): The order of actions has been updated to correctly choose the Fusion Strike Pokmon before searching the deck.
Behavior of the Collect button has been updated to show only on the lowest collectible tier instead of every unlocked tier.
Redeeming a code before product release will now display a message with the number of days until the code is active.

Displaying and scrolling Big Card View in the Deck Editor has been updated for improved visibility.

Card variant thumbnails updated to more accurately display alternate variations.

Currency needed to exchange for Shiny Pokmon VMAX has been updated to 1250 Credits.
